    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1907-11-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1907-11-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="113"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d113">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 551/78.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Chargé <persName type="from">Fletcher</persName> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>,<date calendar="gregorian" when="1907-11-02">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 2, 1907</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 778.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to Mr. RockhilPs No. 703 of August
                        19<note n="a" xml:id="d113fna">Not printed.</note> and No. 722 of September
                    11 last I have the honor to report that a settlement <pb facs="0250" n="138"
                        xml:id="pg_138"/> of the Northern Manchurian customs question has been
                    reached by the Russian minister and the Waiwu Pu, in accordance with which goods
                    upon entering the railway zone will pay two-thirds of the regular import duty;
                    if transported from this zone and the fixed areas into Manchuria they will pay
                    an additional one-third of the import duty, and if transported thence into China
                    proper they will be subject to a surtax equal to one-half of the full duty. This
                    arrangement to be in force for one year. A joint commission is at present
                    arranging the details at Harbin, and its is expected that customs collections
                    will begin to be made very soon. A commissioner of the imperial maritime customs
                    has already been ordered north to inaugurate the service.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Henry P. Fletcher.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
